reviews.review_text:
Terrapin Station > Let It Grow My very first impression through the first minute of Jack Straw and this upload is that it runs slow (to my ears anyway).  If this is really the actual speed of the performance... yikes!  It’s moribund.  Whether it is or it isn’t naturally lethargic, I added 5 ½ percent more speed to liven it up.  It now sounds much better, being peppy and energetic.  Also added a good dose of reverb in Sound Forge for the sterile board and the up-front vocals.  I really like c-freedom's description - "...a very laid back 1st set with no particular hurry to arrive at any certain destination."  That's funny, and just exactly perfect.  

Jerry struggled with singing throughout the year.  Thankfully, he did a good job tonight, which was a big help in recommending the evening. Greatly appreciate the work to get the matrix done and up. 

The first set is average great.  Enjoyed having TLEO, Stagger Lee, Row Jimmy, and Jack-A-Roe from Jer in the same set.  But I hade to laugh again at Bobby’s Minglewood. I reviewed the 9/4 MSG show years ago and remarked at the horrible version Bob sang. After hearing this, it’s not surprising his lack of conviction with that Minglewood 48 hours later at The Garden.  “Bobby doing his best impression of Pat Boone...” is exactly how I heard it again tonight.  “...As soul-less and whitebread as you can get.  I can just picture him snapping his fingers and swiveling his hips.  It’s sad.  Pig would have been embarrassed.  Ain't stealin' any women from their men 2nite.” Only tonight, it might be a little worse.  I’m betting it’s the worse version he ever did. Hey, nobody’s perfect.  Xoxo.  

I decided to start the second set with Terrapin.  For me, the transition into Let It Grow was the curiosity of the evening.  And it’s very good being so smooth, you’d think they were meant to flow that way; sort of like M&MU > Mexicali, Scarlet > Fire, or Estimated > Eyes... with an impressive Grow Jam to boot!  Drumz was cut completely along with a lot of Space on each end to make a very respectable 52:05 minutes of Terrapin > Let It Grow > Jam > Space > Stella > Truckin’ > My Own Fault > U.S. Blues to make a very collectible partial set.  

If you listen closely, Hunter does a masterful job synching and fading Rolfe's AUD in and out of at least three bad SBD cuts so that you barely notice the otherwise major blemishes.  Nice job Mr.Seamons.  With all the problems noted and not noted here, this is a solid above average show with the matrix bumping it up half a star to four.

Ask the time .. I don't know A transition period for the band.
Brent is wise to get comfy in the jams
while adding some laid back Southern California backing vocals.
As much as I loved a hometown show at MSG
I so much preferred the out of town road trips
Discovering the wonders of nature.
This is a still a few years before i would be dancin to the GD.
Although I was going to concerts like YES in the round
having no clue what was going down at the time.

This show itself is nice, a very laid back 1st set
with no particular hurry to arrive at any certain destination
I was thinking about the cowboy tunes from Weir
The different combination of:
Me & My Uncle, Mexicali, Big River,Mama Tried
So just to say those double shots were unique to the post hiatus period and actually just about disappeared when Weir started expanding his repertoire with Dylan tunes post 87 .
In defense of Weir, He is not of the Pigpen generation of blues men
but I know he could get almost any Hippie Chick in his day
Not too many of us can make that claim.
When I was young reckless and wild,
I would walk down the street singing and humming MINGLEWOOD
and prowling like a Dire Wolf..
Pretty obvious that the Jerry tunes especially like in 1st sets
tend to be a little bit sweeter than Weirs offerings
but when I add it all up it flows.
Somehow, someway it adds up to a satisfying musical departure.
A neat thing about this show is getting MUSIC 1st set
and then getting a king size Let it Grow in Set two.
 Music is the most open ended tune of the 1st set
SAMSON- every night like 76 still alright

Great tune selection and jamming pre-drums 
taking the Let it Grow into uncharted territory .

Very sweet Stella with Jerry breathing into the lyrics
Nice backdoor transition into >
The Truckin' has some verse trainwrecks 
but the crescendo jam to close is all that.

Decent Around x2 with everyone so pumped
a good example of the music playing the band.

The Soundboard cuts towards the end of Around
Sometime that's the sound you got stuck with at a show . 
So thankful for these well preserved recordings and for Hunter making this into a Matrix giving us the best of all possibilities.
Sweet recording!

"I am not what I ought to be, I am not what I want to be, 
I am not what I hope to be in another world; 
but still I am not what I once used to be, 
and by the grace of God I am what I am”
― John Newton
